== FactHarbor Organisation ==

Open-source applications and web services for AI-powered fact-checking — every verdict backed by evidence you can inspect.
(((
(% class="box infomessage" style="background-color: #fde0e4; color: #b71c1c;" %)
(((
**Mission:**
FactHarbor brings clarity and transparency to a world full of unclear, contested, and misleading information by shedding light on the context, assumptions, and evidence behind claims.
)))
)))

(% class="box warningmessage" %)
(((
**Public-Interest and Transparent**
FactHarbor is a strictly **Open-Source** project with a clear public-interest orientation.
The goal is full transparency — no hidden algorithms, inspectable evidence trails, and a governance model that is being formalized.
)))

(% class="box infomessage" style="background-color:#eef3f8;border-color:#9db4cb;" %)
(((
The FactHarbor **[[Verein>>https://github.com/robertschaub/FactHarbor/blob/main/Docs/Legal/DRAFT_Vereinsstatuten_FactHarbor_DE.md]]** is currently in preparation. The legal structure is therefore best understood as planned rather than already established.
)))

== Cooperation Opportunities ==

(% class="box successmessage" style="background-color:#e5f4bf;border-color:#7fb36a;" %)
(((
**Highest-priority needs right now:**

* **Speed and cost reduction** — today the system is useful, but still too slow and too expensive for large-scale public use
* **Stability and reproducibility** — repeated runs should converge more reliably instead of producing avoidable verdict variance
* **Evidence retrieval precision and coverage** — retrieval must surface the most decision-relevant evidence more consistently, with fewer wasted searches
* **Claim normalization and multilingual robustness** — inputs vary widely in phrasing, language, and implicitness, especially in international-market settings
)))

(% class="box successmessage" style="background-color:#e5f4bf;border-color:#7fb36a;" %)
(((
**Best collaboration starting points:**

* **Small models for high-volume subtasks** — strongest immediate lever for lowering latency and cost in Stage 1 and Stage 2 screening
* **Low-latency retrieval / RAG** — strongest immediate lever for making evidence acquisition practical at interactive speeds
* **Evaluation and reproducibility** — strongest scientific lever for turning the current alpha system into a publishable, benchmarked research platform, especially with clear **F1**, **MRR@5**, and report-stability baselines ([[details>>||anchor="HWhattheResearchPartnerGains"]])
* **Prototype-and-measure collaboration** — test one or two high-leverage improvements directly in FactHarbor instead of starting with a broad research programme
* **Shared evaluation data and annotation work** — use ViClaim, CheckThat!, and targeted FactHarbor examples to create compact evaluation sets for the most important failure modes
* **Student theses and publication outputs** — focused subprojects and shared-task submissions provide low-risk ways to start collaboration and generate early results
)))

(% class="box successmessage" style="background-color:#e5f4bf;border-color:#7fb36a;" %)
(((
**Medium- and longer-term research directions**:

* **Reproducible fact-checking testbed** — per-job config snapshots, schema versioning, and configurable pipeline stages make FactHarbor useful not just as a product prototype, but as a platform for publishable baseline-vs-variant studies. ([[details>>||anchor="HWhattheResearchPartnerGains"]])
* **Long-term goal: Real-Time Fact Checking** — live or near-live verification of audio, video, and mixed-media streams is a later-stage target, but it depends first on better claim detection, lower latency, and cheaper evidence acquisition. ([[details>>||anchor="HResearchOverlap"]])
* **Federated fact-checking** — a medium-term research question: how to reconcile conflicting verdicts across independent instances, detect cross-node contradictions, and maintain quality guarantees in a decentralized network. ([[details>>||anchor="HTarget3AFederatedNetwork28V2.02B29"]])
* **Community and collaboration layer** — shared work on claims: expert input, joint annotation, comparative fact-check views, and team-based workflows. ([[details>>||anchor="HCommunity26Collaboration"]])
)))

