== Why Collaborate: Mutual Benefits ==

FactHarbor's product ambition is international, and the current collaboration discussion keeps partner and funding options open rather than prioritizing a single institution or instrument. That collaboration is not one-directional — both sides bring what the other needs.

=== What FactHarbor Gains ===

|=Benefit|=Why It Matters
|**Rigorous evaluation methodology**|Research on claim detection (ViClaim, CheckThat!), evidence quality (DIRAS), and source attribution (ACL 2024) points to stronger evaluation protocols. FactHarbor currently evaluates quality informally; formal benchmarks would make the system more academically credible.
|**Research framing**|A research partnership would help turn internal quality checks into publishable evaluation questions, benchmark protocols, and ablation studies — framed as "resource-efficient fact verification" rather than pure engineering.
|**Access to research infrastructure**|University compute, multilingual NLP datasets (ViClaim, CheckThat! corpora), and broader academic collaboration networks and relevant NLP research communities.
|**Grant vehicle**|Possible routes include Innosuisse Innovation Cheque / Innovation Project, SNSF, Hasler Foundation, BRIDGE, and Horizon Europe, depending on partner, scope, and project maturity.
|**Publication pipeline**|Joint papers at top venues (ACL, EMNLP, CLEF CheckThat!) create visibility and attract contributors. ViClaim (EMNLP 2025 main) shows this is achievable.
|**Student contributors**|Bachelor/Master thesis projects on specific pipeline components — a practical, low-risk way to explore focused research questions within the pipeline.

(% class="box successmessage" style="background-color:#e5f4bf;border-color:#7fb36a;" %)
(((
**Summary:** FactHarbor mainly gains formal evaluation methods, research framing, infrastructure access, and credible paths to funding and publications.
)))

=== What the Research Partner Gains ===

|=Benefit|=Why It Matters
|**A working alpha testbed**|Unlike many research prototypes, FactHarbor already runs end-to-end on real claims and produces inspectable artifacts. That makes it useful as an experimental platform, while still being honest about current Alpha-stage limitations.
|**Modular research testbed**|An end-to-end multi-agent debate system with live evidence retrieval is available as a concrete experimental platform. Each pipeline stage produces inspectable intermediate artifacts, and analysis parameters are configurable via UCM with per-job config snapshots for reproducibility.
|**Domain-agnostic scope**|Current academic fact-checking research (HAMiSoN, Climinator, CheckThat!) often focuses on specific domains (social media campaigns, climate claims). FactHarbor provides a **general-domain, topic-agnostic** setting for testing claim detection, evidence retrieval, and verification beyond a single topical area.
|**Publishable open problems**|Resource-efficient pipeline distillation, multilingual verdict stability, evidence sufficiency bounds, report stability metrics, and cross-provider debate dynamics are all concrete topics that can support papers.
|**Applied implementation partner**|FactHarbor can serve as the concrete implementation partner and real-world validation environment in collaborative projects — the applied side that complements academic research.
|**Open-source visibility**|Contributions to an open-source, public-interest project are visible, citable, and reusable by the community — not locked behind a corporate NDA.

(% class="box successmessage" style="background-color:#e5f4bf;border-color:#7fb36a;" %)
(((
**Summary:** Research partners mainly gain a modular, topic-agnostic Alpha-stage research testbed with real artifacts, concrete open problems, and a plausible applied implementation partner.
)))

